into downtown Detroit, midtown
Detroit with Chartreuse?

00:11:05.396 --> 00:11:07.520
And I think-- and correct
me if I have this wrong--

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:09.290
but I think there's a connection
to one of the chefs we've

00:11:09.290 --> 00:11:10.770
already had in, James
Rigato, in terms

00:11:10.770 --> 00:11:11.910
of making an introduction.

00:11:11.910 --> 00:11:13.077
I'd love to hear about that.

00:11:13.077 --> 00:11:14.951
DOUGLAS HEWITT: Yeah,
so it's no secret James

00:11:14.951 --> 00:11:16.460
and I are really good friends.

00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:17.990
We have been for
a very long time.

00:11:17.990 --> 00:11:19.160
We both went to the
same high school,

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:20.201
grew up in the same town.

00:11:20.201 --> 00:11:21.680
Brendon Edwards, too, actually.

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:22.887
He's a Howell guy, too.

00:11:22.887 --> 00:11:24.470
SPEAKER: All the
good chefs in Detroit

00:11:24.470 --> 00:11:25.570
are coming from
Howell, in case you're

00:11:25.570 --> 00:11:26.850
looking for the next big thing.

00:11:26.850 --> 00:11:27.630
Let's go check out Howell.

00:11:27.630 --> 00:11:29.588
DOUGLAS HEWITT: It's
like, what's in the water?

00:11:29.588 --> 00:11:30.196
Like nothing.

00:11:30.196 --> 00:11:32.570
I don't know if it was a lack
of salt growing up or what,

00:11:32.570 --> 00:11:36.370
but we all had to get out of
here and do something else.

00:11:36.370 --> 00:11:38.120
SPEAKER: James didn't
have the best things

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:39.300
to say about Howell either.

00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:40.670
He was not very
uncensored about it,

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:41.520
so good chefs that
get out of there.

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:42.790
DOUGLAS HEWITT: Well, unlike
James, I like Howell--

00:11:42.790 --> 00:11:44.030
SPEAKER: That's
good to know, good.

00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:45.750
DOUGLAS HEWITT: --because
I still live there.

00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:47.375
That's where my house
is, so for now, I

00:11:47.375 --> 00:11:49.790
have to say things like that.

00:11:49.790 --> 00:11:56.170
But yeah, I think if any of
you sat in the room with James,

00:11:56.170 --> 00:11:59.380
you already know there's a huge
difference between James and I.

00:11:59.380 --> 00:12:03.160
But there is a common bond, and
that's our friendship and food.

00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:10.960
So from Ann Arbor, or Dexter--
excuse me-- come to Detroit.

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:13.460
So James is one of my
best customers out there,

00:12:13.460 --> 00:12:14.710
and he kind of knew Doug food.

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:16.450
Like James has
probably eaten my food

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:19.515
more than he's eaten
any other food,

00:12:19.515 --> 00:12:21.640
and I'm thankful for that,
because because of that,

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:23.056
a lot of opportunity
has happened.

00:12:23.056 --> 00:12:26.200
So he's the one that kind
of put Sandy and I together.

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:28.600
If you don't know,
Sandy Levine and I

00:12:28.600 --> 00:12:31.950
are partners at Chartreuse.

00:12:31.950 --> 00:12:33.990
He owns the Oakland
Ferndale, so sort

00:12:33.990 --> 00:12:37.800
of like a speakeasy
cocktail bar kind of thing.

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:40.210
And he put us in contact
in saying he really wanted

00:12:40.210 --> 00:12:41.460
to get back in the restaurant.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:48.090
I really wanted to get back to
Detroit, and within two weeks,

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:50.190
we signed a lease.

00:12:50.190 --> 00:12:52.910
And nine months from that point
on, we opened a restaurant.

00:12:52.910 --> 00:12:55.597
And it's been pretty awesome.

00:12:55.597 --> 00:12:57.930
SPEAKER: How did you guys go
about the conceptualization

00:12:57.930 --> 00:12:59.910
of what Chartreuse has become?

00:12:59.910 --> 00:13:02.940
Was there a clear vision right
up front when you sat down

00:13:02.940 --> 00:13:05.970
to speak with Sandy, or did
it take some time to develop?

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:06.420
DOUGLAS HEWITT: Yeah, I think--

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:07.980
SPEAKER: Was it going to be
like a chicken wing restaurant,

00:13:07.980 --> 00:13:08.370
and then all of a sudden--

00:13:08.370 --> 00:13:10.130
DOUGLAS HEWITT: No, no, no, no.

00:13:10.130 --> 00:13:13.830
No, it was very important
to me that I was

00:13:13.830 --> 00:13:16.172
able to do what I'm good at.

00:13:16.172 --> 00:13:17.880
Obviously, we all want
to be comfortable,

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:20.592
and especially when we're doing
such pride in stepping out

00:13:20.592 --> 00:13:22.050
of our comfort
zone, you really got

00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:24.580
to bring something
you're familiar with.

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:28.050
So it was really important to
me that I kept that sort of--

00:13:28.050 --> 00:13:30.600
I don't want to beat farm
to table in the face.

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:34.056
It's becoming sort
of a cliche in a way.

00:13:34.056 --> 00:13:35.430
But it was really
important to me

00:13:35.430 --> 00:13:38.280
that I could have the
relationship with the food,

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:40.260
I could touch the food.

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:44.430
We wanted a smaller joint,
because I don't really

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:46.020
want to be a clipboard guy.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:49.280
So I really want to
touch food every day.

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:52.340
I want to be a part
of what we're doing.

00:13:52.340 --> 00:13:56.750
So because of that-- and
obviously, being in Dexter,

00:13:56.750 --> 00:13:58.760
really, I was really
starting to get

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:02.360
a pretty good base of Dexter
farmers that I was using.

00:14:02.360 --> 00:14:05.300
And that was really
addicting to me.

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:07.640
And being in Detroit, there's--

00:14:07.640 --> 00:14:12.380
I'm able to get to so many
more places than Dexter.

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:14.330
So that was really cool for me.

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:19.360
And then obviously, Chartreuse
being Sandy's favorite liqueur,

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:21.500
but you'll hear kind of
the story about Chartreuse

00:14:21.500 --> 00:14:22.375
here in a little bit.

00:14:22.375 --> 00:14:26.175
But we thought that it kind
of fit both of our angles.

00:14:26.175 --> 00:14:28.050
So really, that was the
most important thing.

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:29.716
And that's really
what Sandy wanted too.

00:14:29.716 --> 00:14:33.440
We wanted a simple restaurant,
and that's really all it is.

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:34.880
I mean it's a very casual place.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:38.870
If you've been there, you
know, there is no dress code.

00:14:38.870 --> 00:14:41.370
I mean you could come in wearing
anything, doing anything.

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:42.411
It really doesn't matter.

00:14:42.411 --> 00:14:46.380
We're happy to have people come
and enjoy what we're up to.

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:47.810
And that was really it.

00:14:47.810 --> 00:14:50.672
We wanted to feel like we were
inviting people into our house,

00:14:50.672 --> 00:14:52.630
and I think you'll see
that with the build out.

00:14:52.630 --> 00:14:54.150
Kind of necessity, too.

00:14:54.150 --> 00:14:55.260
Don't get me wrong.

00:14:55.260 --> 00:14:57.764
But because of that build out,
before we signed the lease,

00:14:57.764 --> 00:14:59.930
we decided, all right, this
is how it's going to be.

00:14:59.930 --> 00:15:02.370
We want people coming
into our living rooms,

00:15:02.370 --> 00:15:06.650
our home, hide from
nothing, simplicity,

00:15:06.650 --> 00:15:09.650
let food be what it is,
and see what happens.

00:15:09.650 --> 00:15:13.580
And the first year
was pretty awesome.

00:15:13.580 --> 00:15:17.450
We were able to win a
few awards and honeymoon

00:15:17.450 --> 00:15:20.292
the second time, which was
really good business-wise.

00:15:20.292 --> 00:15:22.250
And from that point on,
we haven't looked back.

00:15:22.250 --> 00:15:23.250
SPEAKER: That's awesome.

00:15:23.250 --> 00:15:25.330
And kind of starting to
transition a little bit

00:15:25.330 --> 00:15:28.430
into Michelle and her story,
as we kind of converge

00:15:28.430 --> 00:15:31.640
these things, so if you guys
haven't been to Chartreuse,

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:34.940
vegetables play a massive
role in what you guys produce

00:15:34.940 --> 00:15:38.480
and the plates that you guys
bring to the table every night.

00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:40.910
I read a free press article,
"Detroit Free Press"

00:15:40.910 --> 00:15:43.825
article, that described
you as a vegetable wizard.

00:15:43.825 --> 00:15:45.950
I don't know if you put
that on your business card,

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:49.097
but if you don't, you
should, because it's awesome.

00:15:49.097 --> 00:15:51.430
One thing-- and again, correct
me if I'm wrong in this--

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:55.470
that Chartreuse is
a quaint kitchen,

00:15:55.470 --> 00:15:58.460
and there was not enough room
for a big walk-in freezer

00:15:58.460 --> 00:15:59.450
or cooler.

00:15:59.450 --> 00:16:02.840
And as such-- and again, with
this background of vegetables,

00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:05.300
you weren't able to freeze
vegetables or keep them cold.

00:16:05.300 --> 00:16:07.430
So as they come in
fresh, you basically

00:16:07.430 --> 00:16:09.770
turn them around and put
them right back on the table.

00:16:09.770 --> 00:16:10.850
So there's no freezing.

00:16:10.850 --> 00:16:14.630
There's no preservation from
kind of that type of concept.

00:16:14.630 --> 00:16:16.442
So the vegetables in
the food that you get

00:16:16.442 --> 00:16:17.900
are incredibly
fresh, even compared

00:16:17.900 --> 00:16:20.210
to a lot of other restaurants
that say they do it fresh.

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:21.790
A lot of times, they're
freezing the vegetables.

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:23.480
So I think that's a
really cool kind of aspect

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:24.770
of the way you guys do things.

00:16:24.770 --> 00:16:26.500
It's kind of a
necessity based on size,

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:29.990
but it's also a big plus as well
and what's got you guys a lot

00:16:29.990 --> 00:16:30.615
of recognition.

00:16:30.615 --> 00:16:32.489
DOUGLAS HEWITT: Yeah,
sometimes less is more.

00:16:32.489 --> 00:16:34.340
Sometimes your biggest
challenge ends up

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:38.680
being your biggest
asset or your ally.

00:16:41.850 --> 00:16:45.800
It was very terrifying at
Chartreuse, not, for one,

00:16:45.800 --> 00:16:47.612
having just--

00:16:47.612 --> 00:16:49.070
you can't get three
guys in a line.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:49.940
That's unheard of.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:51.500
When you're feeding
over 1,000 people

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:53.434
a week with two
guys on the line,

00:16:53.434 --> 00:16:55.850
and then, obviously, the garde
manger and stuff like that.

00:16:55.850 --> 00:16:56.808
It was very terrifying.

00:16:56.808 --> 00:16:57.770
I didn't really think--

00:16:57.770 --> 00:17:00.395
I didn't really know how we were
going to actually pull it off.

00:17:00.395 --> 00:17:02.810
We got kind of lucky, you know.

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:06.349
So we found that, all
right, well, let's try

00:17:06.349 --> 00:17:11.119
to buy as much-- as fresh as
we can, as much as we can,

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:16.109
meaning on days to days to days,
and it just kind of worked out.

00:17:16.109 --> 00:17:20.204
And we do a lot of
things raw, and maybe it

00:17:20.204 --> 00:17:21.079
was good timing, too.

00:17:21.079 --> 00:17:22.298
I don't know.

00:17:22.298 --> 00:17:24.589
It felt like we were kind of
composing vegetable plates

00:17:24.589 --> 00:17:26.505
that other people weren't
doing, which you see

00:17:26.505 --> 00:17:27.960
at a lot of restaurants now.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:30.810
Not that we're cutting edge or
we started a trend or anything.

00:17:30.810 --> 00:17:34.250
I just think that we kind of
were the first ones there.

00:17:34.250 --> 00:17:37.070
So we got a lot of hype for
vegetables, and we should have.

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:39.470
There's a lot of great
farmers like Michelle

00:17:39.470 --> 00:17:42.980
doing unbelievable work, and we
just wanted to showcase them.

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:45.894
Add a little salt to a tomato
that was picked that morning.

00:17:45.894 --> 00:17:47.810
You don't need a chef
to tell you that's good.

00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:48.685
You know what I mean?

00:17:48.685 --> 00:17:53.960
So it's just really good
food that we try to not ruin.

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:57.890
And because of it, we
were really successful.

00:17:57.890 --> 00:17:59.360
But yeah, the size
of the kitchen

00:17:59.360 --> 00:18:04.250
really ended up turning out to
be sort of our secret weapon.

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:07.350
It's really hard to overthink
things if you can't.

00:18:07.350 --> 00:18:08.930
So that's kind of how it was.

00:18:08.930 --> 00:18:10.850
SPEAKER: That's fantastic.

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:12.320
Good segue over to Michelle now.

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:16.050
We'd love to hear a little
bit about your position.

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:18.320
And Recovery Park now--

00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:19.950
for those of you
that don't know--

00:18:19.950 --> 00:18:22.600
was founded in 2010, so
about seven years ago.

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:26.460
And the farm aspect was
brought in a few years later.

00:18:26.460 --> 00:18:28.290
This was-- timing, Chef.

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:31.250
You mentioned timing is a
key concept around Detroit.

00:18:31.250 --> 00:18:32.660
Timing is everything.

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:35.000
10 years ago, you didn't
want to be in Detroit.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.510
Now everyone wants
to be in Detroit,

00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:38.120
and timing is a big thing.

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:39.662
For Recovery Park,
I think the timing

00:18:39.662 --> 00:18:41.619
was excellent in terms
of when it was developed

00:18:41.619 --> 00:18:42.330
and what it does.

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:44.371
So Michelle, maybe you
can tell us a little bit--

00:18:44.371 --> 00:18:47.800
excuse me-- a little bit about
Recovery Park and Recovery Park

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:50.350
Farms and what that
concept is and how

00:18:50.350 --> 00:18:53.909
it was established and built
within downtown Detroit.

00:18:53.909 --> 00:18:56.200
MICHELLE LUTZ: So believe it
or not, the idea goes back

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:59.950
to 2008, where our president
and CEO, a gentleman

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:03.040
by the name of Gary
Wozniak, was helping

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:07.150
to right size an organization,
SHAR, Self Help Addiction

00:19:07.150 --> 00:19:08.710
Rehabilitation.

00:19:08.710 --> 00:19:12.070
And the idea was, how
do you help people

00:19:12.070 --> 00:19:14.200
that are trying to stay clean?

00:19:14.200 --> 00:19:18.380
And finding employment,
but meaningful employment

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:22.130
was one of the top conversations
that kept coming up.

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:25.210
So I'll never forget the day
that I got a call from him,

00:19:25.210 --> 00:19:25.990
and I was--

00:19:25.990 --> 00:19:30.910
I had left Detroit in '94 and
bought an 80-acre farm in Yale.

00:19:30.910 --> 00:19:33.100
Kind of Doug's and I's
stories are so similar.

00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:34.640
It's kind of crazy.

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:37.330
So I go up to this town in
Yale, and I buy an 80-acre farm.

00:19:37.330 --> 00:19:39.560
I have no idea what I'm doing.

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:41.570
I'm not born in a
farming background,

00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:44.830
nor have any idea
what I'm about to do.

00:19:44.830 --> 00:19:49.390
But by 2008, I have
had a little success

00:19:49.390 --> 00:19:51.140
and started to
learn a few things.

00:19:51.140 --> 00:19:53.170
And he approached me
and said, what do you

00:19:53.170 --> 00:19:55.640
think about the idea
of farming in Detroit?

00:19:55.640 --> 00:19:56.890
I said, well, I love the idea.

00:19:56.890 --> 00:19:58.598
He said, what do you
think about the idea

00:19:58.598 --> 00:20:00.940
about employing
people who are trying

00:20:00.940 --> 00:20:02.560
to rehabilitate their lives?

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:04.570
And I said, well, it's
a phenomenal idea,

00:20:04.570 --> 00:20:08.322
because to me, agriculture
is very therapeutic.

00:20:08.322 --> 00:20:10.780
There's so much that you can
work out and leave in the soil

00:20:10.780 --> 00:20:12.940
if you're having a bad day.

00:20:12.940 --> 00:20:18.430
And it's something that you
can see the direct impact.

00:20:18.430 --> 00:20:20.570
You see the results
of what you work on.

00:20:20.570 --> 00:20:22.670
So I think for that, it
can be very challenging,

00:20:22.670 --> 00:20:25.030
but it can also be
extremely rewarding.

00:20:25.030 --> 00:20:27.530
And at that time,
it was just an idea.

00:20:27.530 --> 00:20:29.320
And he said, would you help?

00:20:29.320 --> 00:20:32.200
And I said, absolutely,
however I can help.

00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:35.920
So my help along
the years was really

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:38.560
kind of like they would throw
out an idea, a business plan.

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:39.910
What do you think
if we just did that?

00:20:39.910 --> 00:20:41.130
And I'd say, oh,
that's a horrible idea.

00:20:41.130 --> 00:20:41.990
Don't do that.

00:20:41.990 --> 00:20:42.990
Well, what should we do?

00:20:42.990 --> 00:20:45.610
And I kind of just kept saying,
look at what the market needs.

00:20:45.610 --> 00:20:47.050
Try to address.

00:20:47.050 --> 00:20:50.660
And my heart was
still in the city.

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:53.890
People would always say
to us, why can't you

00:20:53.890 --> 00:20:56.740
just do this down in Detroit?

00:20:56.740 --> 00:21:00.890
And I said, well, give us
80 acres, and we'll do it.

00:21:00.890 --> 00:21:03.550
But back then, that
wasn't happening.

00:21:03.550 --> 00:21:06.370
With the administration
that we had, it wasn't--

00:21:06.370 --> 00:21:09.940
no one was willing to do that.

00:21:09.940 --> 00:21:12.590
But our connection to the
city was still very clear.

00:21:12.590 --> 00:21:16.780
I mean we had CSA drop-offs,
like when Avalon first opened,

00:21:16.780 --> 00:21:19.830
that was our first CSA
drop-off way back then.

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:22.570
We had CSA drop-offs
on Rosa Parks,

00:21:22.570 --> 00:21:26.680
and we fed shelters and
firehouses, and so very much

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:30.400
still, hitting the city
with our food twice a week.

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:33.460
And the funny thing
for me, though,

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.380
is I never thought
that it would lead

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:37.270
to a career with Recovery Park.

00:21:37.270 --> 00:21:40.060
I never thought that I would
actually be farming for them.

00:21:40.060 --> 00:21:43.900
So life happens, and I
left my farm in 2011,

00:21:43.900 --> 00:21:47.590
and I did a project over for
Henry Ford Health Care Systems.

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:52.700
I opened up a greenhouse behind
their West Bloomfield facility.

00:21:52.700 --> 00:21:55.360
And I was having a lot of
fun over there doing that.

00:21:55.360 --> 00:21:58.990
And then Gary came to
me in 2013, and he said,

00:21:58.990 --> 00:22:01.090
we're at the point
now that we've

00:22:01.090 --> 00:22:05.680
got to start proving out the
whole ag part of the business.

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:07.490
And would you come
and farm for us?

00:22:07.490 --> 00:22:09.200
Will you do a pilot
project for us?

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:12.340
And I had 100%
confidence in the idea

00:22:12.340 --> 00:22:14.620
that we would grow specialty
produce and grow it

00:22:14.620 --> 00:22:18.400
locally and get it to
chefs as fresh as possible.

00:22:18.400 --> 00:22:20.360
So I was like, sure.

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:22.420
So the very first thing
that we did in 2014

00:22:22.420 --> 00:22:24.572
is we built a high
tunnel, which is

00:22:24.572 --> 00:22:26.530
one of those structures
over there on the wall.

00:22:26.530 --> 00:22:29.500
We call them high tunnels.

00:22:29.500 --> 00:22:33.490
We built one in a parking lot
off of East Grand Boulevard

00:22:33.490 --> 00:22:36.080
and made brazed beds in it
and filled it with compost

00:22:36.080 --> 00:22:37.330
that we brought in.

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:40.480
And that was the very
first year that we grew.

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:44.620
And to no surprise,
it was working.

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:48.640
People want--
finally, it's the time

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:52.790
where chefs are so prone to
say, yes, this is what we want.

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:53.980
We want to know the grower.

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:56.410
We want to be able to
go and see the food

00:22:56.410 --> 00:22:58.780
and have a relationship
and talk about what

00:22:58.780 --> 00:23:00.970
I wanted to see on the menu.

00:23:00.970 --> 00:23:03.287
And we tried to do
this 10 years ago.

00:23:03.287 --> 00:23:04.870
I mean I remember
when I first started

00:23:04.870 --> 00:23:06.130
trying to sell to shops.

00:23:06.130 --> 00:23:08.750
It was like, what?

00:23:08.750 --> 00:23:09.880
What are you talking about?

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:11.338
No, it's got to
come through Cisco.

00:23:11.338 --> 00:23:13.030
It's got to come
through US Foods.

00:23:13.030 --> 00:23:14.440
We can't cut you a check.

00:23:14.440 --> 00:23:15.100
It's got to go.

00:23:15.100 --> 00:23:17.980
I mean it was such a
complicated ordeal.

00:23:17.980 --> 00:23:20.590
So to start doing that was--

00:23:20.590 --> 00:23:23.320
by 2014, what I'm trying to
say, I had a lot of confidence,

00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:24.550
that the time was--

00:23:24.550 --> 00:23:26.710
we had enough chefs
out there that

00:23:26.710 --> 00:23:28.630
were ready to do
this, ready to have

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:33.139
you deliver a box of produce
and make something today.

00:23:33.139 --> 00:23:34.930
And then if you brought
them something else

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:36.820
excellent two days
from then, they

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:39.580
were willing to change that.

00:23:39.580 --> 00:23:42.190
A small grower
locally isn't going

00:23:42.190 --> 00:23:44.830
to be-- we're never
going to supply a Subway.

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:48.680
We're never going to
have 500 cases of five

00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:54.220
by fives at some price that you
can't make up or pay a living

00:23:54.220 --> 00:23:55.270
wage off of.

00:23:55.270 --> 00:23:56.677
It's never going to happen.

00:23:56.677 --> 00:23:58.510
So you kind of got to
go in a direction that

00:23:58.510 --> 00:24:02.390
will take your business
to where it needs to go.

00:24:02.390 --> 00:24:05.020
So we've done a few
years of pilot projects,

00:24:05.020 --> 00:24:09.850
waiting for the city to give
us some land that we can really

00:24:09.850 --> 00:24:12.410
execute our idea.

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:15.490
And in the fall
of 2015, the mayor

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:17.500
announced that the
land bank would

00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:19.990
allow us to lease some property
over in the neighborhood

00:24:19.990 --> 00:24:21.240
that we're at right now.

00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:24.920
We're on the east side,
Chene and Ferry area,

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:27.820
to give you some kind of--
we're a couple of miles away

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:30.070
from Eastern Market to
give you some idea of where

00:24:30.070 --> 00:24:31.360
we're located.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:34.660
So it's a very--

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:37.640
it's a very vacant neighborhood.

00:24:37.640 --> 00:24:40.820
What I know about is
that in the 1950s,

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:43.510
there was 100,000 jobs
within walking distance

00:24:43.510 --> 00:24:44.860
of that neighborhood.

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:48.760
2,500 people lived
on a 22-block radius.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:52.940
There are now 17 residents
in that neighborhood.

00:24:52.940 --> 00:24:55.479
So Recovery Park
caretakes that 22 blocks.

00:24:55.479 --> 00:24:56.520
What does that look like?

00:24:56.520 --> 00:24:59.080
Any land that
belongs to the city--

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:00.430
we clean up blight.

00:25:00.430 --> 00:25:03.620
We make sure that any dumping
that goes on gets cleaned up.

00:25:03.620 --> 00:25:05.170
We mow those grasses.

00:25:05.170 --> 00:25:06.860
We keep it clean.

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:09.550
And back in October,
we started building

00:25:09.550 --> 00:25:11.590
what we called Beta
Farm, because we still

00:25:11.590 --> 00:25:13.360
have a lot to learn.

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:15.880
I'm embarrassed to tell you
guys that after 23 years

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:18.400
of doing this, I still
have a lot to learn.

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:21.640
I've never done this in this
type of environment before.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:25.380
The Detroit soil has
so much to offer,

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:27.190
and I mean that
very sarcastically.

00:25:27.190 --> 00:25:29.050
There's so much debris.

00:25:29.050 --> 00:25:32.590
You know, back then, where
there was houses right there,

00:25:32.590 --> 00:25:34.760
this is when they still
just collapsed the houses

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:37.510
into the basements.

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:40.720
So there's a lot of
fun stuff to find.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:42.970
So we started building
those in October,

00:25:42.970 --> 00:25:45.250
and it took a little
longer than it should,

00:25:45.250 --> 00:25:47.200
like any construction project.

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:51.310
But we are now-- we have
eight out of seven structures

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:53.050
completely operational.

00:25:53.050 --> 00:25:55.570
The only reason why the
last one isn't online

00:25:55.570 --> 00:25:57.530
is because Monday, we
plant that with tomatoes

00:25:57.530 --> 00:26:00.700
so that we have a
succession of crop.

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:05.770
And we have six farms
associates working with us.

00:26:05.770 --> 00:26:07.840
The reason why Recovery
Park Farms exists

00:26:07.840 --> 00:26:09.850
is because Recovery
Park, the nonprofit,

00:26:09.850 --> 00:26:13.492
wants to create jobs for people
with barriers to employment.

00:26:13.492 --> 00:26:14.950
But when you're a
nonprofit, you're

00:26:14.950 --> 00:26:16.840
always looking for
funding, right?

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:19.165
So that can be very
unstable to people's lives

00:26:19.165 --> 00:26:20.890
if funding runs out.

00:26:20.890 --> 00:26:22.690
So we decided that
Recovery Park would

00:26:22.690 --> 00:26:26.260
launch for-profit businesses,
so that way, the business can

00:26:26.260 --> 00:26:28.570
stand on its own two
legs, and we can make sure

00:26:28.570 --> 00:26:33.960
that people's lives are not
destabilized at any point.

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:37.000
So we hire people with
barriers to employment.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:38.620
Our farm crew has--

00:26:38.620 --> 00:26:40.690
none of them have
had any experience

00:26:40.690 --> 00:26:44.650
with farming before
or growing anything.

00:26:44.650 --> 00:26:46.690
I was so confident
in our ability

00:26:46.690 --> 00:26:51.130
to train people that I hired
based on personality and work

00:26:51.130 --> 00:26:52.240
ethic.

00:26:52.240 --> 00:26:56.941
And so I'm proud to
say that it's working.

00:26:56.941 --> 00:26:57.940
SPEAKER: That's awesome.

00:26:57.940 --> 00:26:59.950
Thanks for the background.

00:26:59.950 --> 00:27:01.840
I think there's a lot
of questions still

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:03.715
on how you guys got this
up and running, even

00:27:03.715 --> 00:27:05.160
with that detailed description.

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:07.930
It's incredible what you
guys have been able to do.

00:27:07.930 --> 00:27:10.190
Detroit's a unique canvas
for something like this,

00:27:10.190 --> 00:27:13.000
because there's a lot
of underutilized assets.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:18.280
So you've got a massive city
with a million plus people,

00:27:18.280 --> 00:27:20.110
but a lot of empty
and vacant land.

00:27:20.110 --> 00:27:23.320
You've got access to fresh water
with the Detroit River and Lake

00:27:23.320 --> 00:27:28.000
St. Clair so nearby, and
you've got a wanting workforce.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.760
You have folks that
want to work, but maybe

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:33.700
have had issues in the past
or have challenges with it.

00:27:33.700 --> 00:27:36.820
So it's kind of
this really unique

00:27:36.820 --> 00:27:38.320
coming together
of a lot of things

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:41.080
that make this possible,
which I think is fantastic.

00:27:41.080 --> 00:27:43.810
Could you talk a little bit more
before we take a quick break,

00:27:43.810 --> 00:27:46.175
and then talk about how you
guys have come together?

00:27:46.175 --> 00:27:48.550
And you touched on it just a
minute ago about this hiring

00:27:48.550 --> 00:27:49.630
process.

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:53.530
Where do you go to find
these type of employees?

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:58.012
What's your process for bringing
talent in and training them

00:27:58.012 --> 00:28:00.220
and getting them ramped up
on this process of working

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:01.482
within Recovery Park Farms.

00:28:01.482 --> 00:28:03.190
MICHELLE LUTZ: So I
always tell everybody

00:28:03.190 --> 00:28:06.010
we hire the best talent, but
we're completely prepared

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:09.310
to work with people who have
some challenges in life.

00:28:09.310 --> 00:28:11.770
We look within
our own community.

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:14.840
Hiring Detroit residents
is very important to us.

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:18.190
It's one of our conditions
with the city of Detroit

00:28:18.190 --> 00:28:20.980
that such a percentage
of our workforce

00:28:20.980 --> 00:28:22.460
are Detroit residents.

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:26.080
I think we have to have
61% of our workforce.

00:28:26.080 --> 00:28:27.640
We work within the prisons.

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:30.610
We have a relationship with
the Michigan Department

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:32.080
of Corrections.

00:28:32.080 --> 00:28:34.450
It's actually a pretty
solid relationship,

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:40.120
where they are even interested
in adding hydroponic growing

00:28:40.120 --> 00:28:41.710
into some of their
training facilities

00:28:41.710 --> 00:28:44.876
so that we can have more
of a workforce ready.

00:28:44.876 --> 00:28:46.750
It's very important that
when people come out

00:28:46.750 --> 00:28:48.660
of incarceration that
they have employment

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:51.160
and housing immediately.

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:53.230
So they say that a
success is somebody

00:28:53.230 --> 00:28:56.609
who comes out of prison that
doesn't go back in two years.

00:28:56.609 --> 00:28:58.150
You could still be
addicted to drugs.

00:28:58.150 --> 00:28:59.733
You could be living
under an overpass.

00:28:59.733 --> 00:29:01.480
You could be eating
out of a garbage.

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:03.760
That doesn't look
like success to us.

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:07.210
So for us, we want to make sure
that our employees, after 90

00:29:07.210 --> 00:29:10.900
days of full time employment,
have a 100% company paid

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:12.160
health care.

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:16.360
We have someone on staff that
works with all of their needs--

00:29:16.360 --> 00:29:21.940
transportation, housing,
reunification with family,

00:29:21.940 --> 00:29:23.829
religion, all of those areas.

00:29:23.829 --> 00:29:25.870
I can't even list them,
because that's really not

00:29:25.870 --> 00:29:29.600
what my job is on the farm.

00:29:29.600 --> 00:29:33.010
But we have somebody on
staff that does that.

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:36.870
As far as finding people,
we work with Michigan

00:29:36.870 --> 00:29:38.440
Rehabilitative Services.

00:29:38.440 --> 00:29:41.620
So we have SHAR,
that organization.

00:29:41.620 --> 00:29:47.757
We found some of our farm
team from those organizations.

00:29:47.757 --> 00:29:50.090
SPEAKER: And last question
before we take a quick break.

00:29:50.090 --> 00:29:53.420
What does the future look like?

00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:55.900
It seems like you're
getting a lot of support

00:29:55.900 --> 00:29:56.980
from the city of Detroit.

00:29:56.980 --> 00:30:00.250
It seems like you're finding
some really good success, so

00:30:00.250 --> 00:30:01.630
a lot of positive momentum.

00:30:01.630 --> 00:30:05.210
Like what do you see as
the next steps-- expansion,

00:30:05.210 --> 00:30:08.170
just continuing to
perfect what you do?

00:30:08.170 --> 00:30:12.250
Where do you see the vision
of Recovery Parks Farm going?

00:30:12.250 --> 00:30:14.800
MICHELLE LUTZ: So the five-year
plan, when we get there,

00:30:14.800 --> 00:30:19.180
is for us to have 200
employees, that we would

00:30:19.180 --> 00:30:21.010
have 22 acres under glass.

00:30:21.010 --> 00:30:23.890
So if you take a look at that
photo there that I have up,

00:30:23.890 --> 00:30:26.980
that's one city block,
about three acres.

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:29.080
So there are eight
of those structures

00:30:29.080 --> 00:30:31.540
up there, so we'll
have nine acres that

00:30:31.540 --> 00:30:33.230
look something like that.

00:30:33.230 --> 00:30:35.660
And we would have 22 acres
under glass production.

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:37.420
So if you can imagine
a city block but be

00:30:37.420 --> 00:30:39.330
covered in a glass greenhouse.

00:30:39.330 --> 00:30:41.860
In that, we would do
hydroponic growing there.

00:30:41.860 --> 00:30:45.670
But what the coolest thing to me
about that five-year plan is it

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:49.300
shows that Chene Street
comes back with businesses.

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:51.850
It shows opportunities
for housing.

00:30:51.850 --> 00:30:55.730
It shows opportunity for
massive community space.

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:58.940
It also makes sure that the
residents that live there,

00:30:58.940 --> 00:31:00.400
we're not doing
something obnoxious

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:02.800
like putting a greenhouse
right next to them.

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:04.204
We have really
good relationships

00:31:04.204 --> 00:31:05.620
with the neighbors
that are there,

00:31:05.620 --> 00:31:08.350
and we've made sure that
everyone understands

00:31:08.350 --> 00:31:12.040
we're here to help, I
think, make the neighborhood

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:13.540
more beautiful.

00:31:13.540 --> 00:31:15.610
And we want people to stay.

00:31:15.610 --> 00:31:17.730
We're not here to say,
oh, we're here now,

00:31:17.730 --> 00:31:19.240
and we're going to take over.

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:23.230
Within that 22-block area,
we have ample opportunity

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:27.250
and space to do those
things that we want to do.

00:31:27.250 --> 00:31:30.490
SPEAKER: I would love to hear
the story of the convergence

00:31:30.490 --> 00:31:33.851
between the both of you, and you
guys are obviously very close.

00:31:33.851 --> 00:31:35.350
I'm just watching
you guys interact,

00:31:35.350 --> 00:31:38.320
and I know you guys work
together on a daily basis.

00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:41.690
So can you talk a little
bit about the process?

00:31:41.690 --> 00:31:45.110
And maybe, Doug, we can
start from your perspective.

00:31:45.110 --> 00:31:46.570
You've got a
restaurant, or you're

00:31:46.570 --> 00:31:47.986
in the process of
putting together

00:31:47.986 --> 00:31:49.210
a restaurant in Detroit.

00:31:49.210 --> 00:31:51.590
You're looking for
local sourcing.

00:31:51.590 --> 00:31:53.590
How does that process
play into working

00:31:53.590 --> 00:31:55.370
with Michelle and her team?

00:31:55.370 --> 00:31:58.320
DOUGLAS HEWITT: Yeah, I think
we're still looking at a space,

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:02.020
and the place is pretty
much just a shell.

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:05.910
I think Michelle reached
out to me first on Facebook.

00:32:05.910 --> 00:32:07.390
And I was like, thank god.

00:32:07.390 --> 00:32:08.973
I've been meaning
to get a hold of you

00:32:08.973 --> 00:32:14.440
to see if maybe
we can partner up.

00:32:14.440 --> 00:32:16.090
I know a lot of my
friends that were

00:32:16.090 --> 00:32:20.000
chefs in this area before me.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.764
I would see nonstop
Michelle's this,

00:32:22.764 --> 00:32:25.180
Michelle's-- a lot of beets
and radishes, stuff like that.

00:32:25.180 --> 00:32:27.370
And I was like, man, that
food is just unbelievable.

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:29.536
So it was definitely something
I wanted to reach out

00:32:29.536 --> 00:32:30.880
when I came down here.

00:32:30.880 --> 00:32:33.171
It was really important to
me that I brought some farms

00:32:33.171 --> 00:32:35.590
with me, and then I
could reach out and start

00:32:35.590 --> 00:32:38.980
getting some even more local or
some farms that my friends were

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:40.720
using.

00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:43.660
So Michelle reached out to me.

00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:47.500
We met, I don't
know, pretty soon

00:32:47.500 --> 00:32:49.730
after the contact was made.

00:32:49.730 --> 00:32:55.070
And then I said, well,
like what kind of--

00:32:55.070 --> 00:32:56.120
what do you need from me?

00:32:56.120 --> 00:32:58.780
She wants to know what
we want to use and stuff.

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:03.150
And we just basically
said, I don't really care.

00:33:03.150 --> 00:33:06.530
I just want you to
kind of bring me boxes.

00:33:06.530 --> 00:33:09.209
And then I could kind of just--
it's kind of a mystery basket

00:33:09.209 --> 00:33:09.750
twice a week.

00:33:09.750 --> 00:33:11.791
You just open it up, and
you see what's in there,

00:33:11.791 --> 00:33:16.160
and just kind of let your
imagination go a little bit.

00:33:16.160 --> 00:33:22.019
And it made me a
better chef by far.

00:33:22.019 --> 00:33:23.810
But really, it was that
sort of excitement.

00:33:23.810 --> 00:33:26.460
And when we are talking
like, hey, how about we call

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:29.710
the dish Recovery Park?

00:33:29.710 --> 00:33:31.517
And she was flattered
by that, too.

00:33:31.517 --> 00:33:33.350
And I was like, sweet,
because that's really

00:33:33.350 --> 00:33:34.308
what I want to call it.

00:33:34.308 --> 00:33:38.900
So our opening menu had a
Recovery Park dish on the menu.

00:33:38.900 --> 00:33:41.770
And outside of the small
transition between properties,

00:33:41.770 --> 00:33:47.150
we've had a Recovery Park item
on the menu since day one.

00:33:47.150 --> 00:33:48.380
And it's just been--

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:49.550
it's really cool.

00:33:49.550 --> 00:33:53.630
It's farm-specific, and
not only farm-specific,

00:33:53.630 --> 00:33:57.440
but a lot of people know--

00:33:57.440 --> 00:33:59.330
Michelle is sort of like--

00:33:59.330 --> 00:34:00.290
I don't know.

