00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:07.920
not just on the farm, but
on the nonprofit side.

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:12.300
We've got great people
like Doug and other people

00:38:12.300 --> 00:38:13.930
that want this to work.

00:38:13.930 --> 00:38:16.560
And then we have consumers like
you guys that go out there,

00:38:16.560 --> 00:38:17.700
so it's--

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:20.190
the whole thing has to
work for this to work.

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:24.630
So that's where all
the produce goes.

00:38:24.630 --> 00:38:29.256
It's really-- I'm so happy
that the marketing part is not

00:38:29.256 --> 00:38:30.630
something I have
to stress about.

00:38:30.630 --> 00:38:37.140
I can just grow and train people
and help people build careers.

00:38:37.140 --> 00:38:40.710
Seriously, after three years
of being with us on this farm,

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:42.210
the guys that we're
working with can

00:38:42.210 --> 00:38:45.270
go anywhere and get really--

00:38:45.270 --> 00:38:47.280
I mean I'll have to
fight to keep them.

00:38:47.280 --> 00:38:51.220
They will be that suited to
work anywhere in the world.

00:38:51.220 --> 00:38:53.580
So that makes me very proud.

00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:55.097
But it's not all about business.

00:38:55.097 --> 00:38:56.430
We have a lot for the community.

00:38:56.430 --> 00:38:59.047
We have a decent-sized
community garden.

00:38:59.047 --> 00:39:00.630
We're still working
on adding to that,

00:39:00.630 --> 00:39:03.030
so we have a
giveback, so that way,

00:39:03.030 --> 00:39:05.700
I don't have to feel bad about
everything being sold off

00:39:05.700 --> 00:39:06.760
the farm.

00:39:06.760 --> 00:39:08.070
SPEAKER: That's awesome.

00:39:08.070 --> 00:39:09.660
I love this idea
of local sourcing.

00:39:09.660 --> 00:39:11.326
Obviously, very
important to both of you

00:39:11.326 --> 00:39:14.235
from distinct perspectives.

00:39:14.235 --> 00:39:16.860
My last question, as we kind of
bring everything back together,

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:20.130
is do you think-- so
again, we talked about this

00:39:20.130 --> 00:39:22.060
being fairly unique to Detroit.

00:39:22.060 --> 00:39:26.280
Do you think
something like this is

00:39:26.280 --> 00:39:29.280
able to be repeated in other
cities or other communities?

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:34.490
We've got some unique physical
aspects in the city of Detroit

00:39:34.490 --> 00:39:36.240
that allow something
like this to happen--

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:40.930
proximity to a major
city, proximity to--

00:39:40.930 --> 00:39:45.120
specific timing and kind of
the renaissance of Detroit.

00:39:45.120 --> 00:39:47.924
Is this something that's just
localized to being something

00:39:47.924 --> 00:39:49.590
that can work in
Detroit, or do you guys

00:39:49.590 --> 00:39:54.219
see something like this being
replicable outside of the city?

00:39:54.219 --> 00:39:56.010
MICHELLE LUTZ: I might
take a stab at that,

00:39:56.010 --> 00:39:57.900
because I certainly hope so.

00:39:57.900 --> 00:40:00.810
I've dedicated the last
23 years of my life

00:40:00.810 --> 00:40:06.260
to helping to build and
strengthen local food systems.

00:40:06.260 --> 00:40:09.080
It is imperative
that you have that.

00:40:09.080 --> 00:40:12.320
So anywhere in the
world, having food

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:14.600
right there in your
community is so important.

00:40:14.600 --> 00:40:17.390
I look at how we've
handled natural disasters.

00:40:17.390 --> 00:40:20.520
I look at how just when
we had the power outage,

00:40:20.520 --> 00:40:22.100
and there was no food coming in.

00:40:22.100 --> 00:40:25.100
We cannot be dependent on
other people feeding us.

00:40:25.100 --> 00:40:27.660
We have to have these
type of relationships.

00:40:27.660 --> 00:40:29.870
This is the only way it works.

00:40:29.870 --> 00:40:32.810
An operation like ours could
not pay people a living wage

00:40:32.810 --> 00:40:34.490
and have health care benefits.

00:40:34.490 --> 00:40:38.820
If I had to do straight
up market pricing,

00:40:38.820 --> 00:40:42.200
compete with large farms in
Mexico that pay people $2

00:40:42.200 --> 00:40:44.200
a week, that system is broken.

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:45.150
It does not work.

00:40:45.150 --> 00:40:47.190
It's heavy on
chemicals, and I'm not

00:40:47.190 --> 00:40:48.440
going to get into all of that.

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:54.860
But if you really want to have a
strong local food system, this,

00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:57.230
all of this-- consumers,
chefs, growers--

00:40:57.230 --> 00:40:58.700
it all has to work.

00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:00.380
And I'm damn proud
of what Detroit

00:41:00.380 --> 00:41:01.910
is doing in that
element, and I'm

00:41:01.910 --> 00:41:05.840
happy that we have as many
outstanding growers that we

00:41:05.840 --> 00:41:10.970
have, and once again, chefs that
are taking advantage of that.

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:14.450
To me, I love when we have
visitors from out of town.

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:17.690
We had a group in from
Paris about a month ago,

00:41:17.690 --> 00:41:20.392
and they were like, this
has to happen in Paris.

00:41:20.392 --> 00:41:21.100
You have to come.

00:41:21.100 --> 00:41:23.170
I was like, no, I still
got work over here to do.

00:41:23.170 --> 00:41:26.680
But it's great to see how people
visit something like that,

00:41:26.680 --> 00:41:30.640
and they feel instantly
that it can be duplicated.

00:41:30.640 --> 00:41:36.470
And to me, that's a great thing.

00:41:36.470 --> 00:41:38.080
Niagara's talked
to Recovery Park.

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:41.350
I mean there's been other cities
that have come in and said,

00:41:41.350 --> 00:41:44.050
once you get this going,
but we've got a lot of it

00:41:44.050 --> 00:41:44.950
still to figure out.

00:41:44.950 --> 00:41:47.040
SPEAKER: Sure.

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:48.970
That's a great
foundation, and it's nice

00:41:48.970 --> 00:41:51.370
when people are looking
to a city like Detroit

00:41:51.370 --> 00:41:54.140
for opportunity and
to replicate things.

00:41:54.140 --> 00:41:56.500
Any last thoughts,
Chef, on your side

00:41:56.500 --> 00:41:58.450
in terms of kind
of sustainability

00:41:58.450 --> 00:41:59.830
of this and kind
of what it looks

00:41:59.830 --> 00:42:01.082
like for you moving forward?

00:42:01.082 --> 00:42:03.040
DOUGLAS HEWITT: Yeah, I
mean when it comes down

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:08.320
to other cities being able to
duplicate exactly what we're

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:09.550
up to, I highly doubt it.

00:42:12.740 --> 00:42:17.720
Some of the unfortunate parts
are our fortune, really,

00:42:17.720 --> 00:42:19.220
being able to go
into neighborhoods,

00:42:19.220 --> 00:42:20.761
and some cities
don't have that much.

00:42:20.761 --> 00:42:22.490
But really what
we have, I think,

00:42:22.490 --> 00:42:29.390
is Detroit as a whole is sort
of a very proud community.

00:42:29.390 --> 00:42:31.010
And food is sort of--

00:42:31.010 --> 00:42:36.920
I think food is sort of at the
forefront of the new Detroit.

00:42:36.920 --> 00:42:39.285
I hate saying new Detroit,
but how do you avoid it?

00:42:39.285 --> 00:42:40.160
You know what I mean?

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:41.680
Because there is
a lot happening.

00:42:41.680 --> 00:42:44.330
There's a lot of new stuff.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:50.030
But I think with as
many chefs and how

00:42:50.030 --> 00:42:54.995
we interact and the farming
system, and the farming

00:42:54.995 --> 00:42:56.870
doesn't work if the
consumer doesn't want it.

00:42:59.390 --> 00:43:02.530
Farming doesn't-- some of these
unique ingredients don't work

00:43:02.530 --> 00:43:06.100
if nobody knows how to use them
or if people are [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:06.100 --> 00:43:08.210
out or weird about it,
those kind of things.

00:43:08.210 --> 00:43:12.530
So and then all of a sudden,
the brewing and the distilling,

00:43:12.530 --> 00:43:15.680
and now all of a
sudden, we have people

00:43:15.680 --> 00:43:19.519
that are bringing Michigan
whole animals to Detroit, where

00:43:19.519 --> 00:43:20.810
we're starting to buy our meat.

00:43:20.810 --> 00:43:23.774
So really, this
was sort of like--

00:43:23.774 --> 00:43:26.190
I think Michelle's movement
was sort of the first movement

00:43:26.190 --> 00:43:29.120
to where everyone's
like, wait a minute.

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:33.170
We can do a lot more
than just produce.

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:34.760
And I think we're starting out--

00:43:34.760 --> 00:43:38.090
as people are starting
work together.

00:43:38.090 --> 00:43:39.140
Go eat anywhere in town.

00:43:39.140 --> 00:43:40.100
Go eat at Grey Ghost.

00:43:40.100 --> 00:43:40.670
Go eat at Selden.

00:43:40.670 --> 00:43:41.545
Go eat at Mabel Gray.

00:43:41.545 --> 00:43:43.504
Go eat at Chartreuse.

00:43:43.504 --> 00:43:45.170
The chances of you
eating an animal that

00:43:45.170 --> 00:43:48.110
wasn't raised in this state
are probably not great,

00:43:48.110 --> 00:43:52.850
outside of some fish and
maybe a couple of the more--

00:43:52.850 --> 00:43:55.190
ducks are more harder
things to come by.

00:43:58.370 --> 00:44:00.915
Either eat the corn bread, and
I guarantee that buttermilk

00:44:00.915 --> 00:44:01.790
was done in Michigan.

00:44:01.790 --> 00:44:02.665
You know what I mean?

00:44:02.665 --> 00:44:05.930
So go eat the egg
dish, and I guarantee

00:44:05.930 --> 00:44:08.920
there's two or three farms
that are doing the farms.

00:44:08.920 --> 00:44:11.960
We've taken just that
twice cooked egg alone,

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:15.170
and then the other restaurants
are taking this small egg guy

00:44:15.170 --> 00:44:20.540
in Mason, Michigan to
like an actual business.

00:44:20.540 --> 00:44:22.310
It was a hobby,
him and his wife.

00:44:22.310 --> 00:44:25.460
And then they got sick
of washing 400,000 eggs

00:44:25.460 --> 00:44:26.240
a week by hand.

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:28.665
And now they have
their son moved back

00:44:28.665 --> 00:44:29.540
to help the business.

00:44:29.540 --> 00:44:31.030
They bought this big washer.

00:44:31.030 --> 00:44:33.355
And we're talking about
five restaurants in Detroit,

00:44:33.355 --> 00:44:34.730
and all of a
sudden, this guy has

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:38.780
a legit business moving eggs,
and we're proud to serve them.

00:44:38.780 --> 00:44:41.240
You know what I mean?

00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:45.740
So it really is this network
of, really, people just trying

00:44:45.740 --> 00:44:47.030
to do the right thing.

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:50.932
But again, it doesn't work if
people don't buy into that.

00:44:50.932 --> 00:44:54.000
If people don't want to know
where their food is from,

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:55.790
and they don't care
about sustainability

00:44:55.790 --> 00:45:00.460
or organic practice or those
kind of things, we're screwed.

00:45:00.460 --> 00:45:00.960
[INAUDIBLE]

00:45:00.960 --> 00:45:01.835
You know what I mean?

